<section class="section section--alt" id="qbo-feat-cash-flow-planner-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What the QuickBooks Online Cash Flow Planner is, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>The Cash Flow Planner is the built-in feature in QuickBooks Online that projects your cash balance forward in time. It starts from your current bank balance and extends it &mdash; typically over the next 30 to 90 days &mdash; by adding the money you&rsquo;re expecting in and the money going out, on the dates each is expected. The point is to give you a near-term look at where your cash is headed without building anything from scratch.</p>
      <p>It doesn&rsquo;t invent any of those numbers. It reads from your books: open invoices represent inflows you&rsquo;re owed, unpaid bills and scheduled or recurring transactions represent outflows, and the Planner places each on its expected date and runs the balance forward. On top of that, you can add <em>manual events</em> &mdash; an expected payment you haven&rsquo;t invoiced, a planned purchase, a loan draw &mdash; to model a scenario and see how it would move the projected balance, all without changing the underlying books.</p>
      <p>The Planner is genuinely useful, but it&rsquo;s worth being precise about what it is not. It&rsquo;s a quick built-in <em>projection</em>, not a full forecast model &mdash; it extrapolates the near term from known and recurring items; it doesn&rsquo;t weigh seasonality, growth assumptions, or multiple scenarios the way real planning does. And a projection is only as good as the books behind it: if invoices and bills aren&rsquo;t entered, the forward view won&rsquo;t reflect them. We describe QuickBooks Online&rsquo;s behavior as it actually works &mdash; we don&rsquo;t claim capabilities the feature doesn&rsquo;t have. For planning beyond the next few weeks, see <a href="/accounting/advisory/cash-flow-management/">cash-flow forecasting</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

